<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>Let's make a baseball analogy. Do you think a person with no hand-eye coordination can become a great hitter?<p>I have no doubt there are people who are math averse who have plenty of untapped math ability (e.g. most women with math ability have been taught to think they can't do math). There are plenty of psychological reasons why a person who is capable of doing something might think they have "zero talent", and it's perfectly plausible for a good mentor to help them unlock their ability. But that's a far cry from the argument that "anyone can be a great programmer".</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=40></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_2903795 href="vote?for=2903795&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%68%5a%65%50%65%56%32%73%76%79"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_2903795></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=pnathan">pnathan</a> 170 days ago  | <a href="item?id=2903795">link</a></span></div><br>
